ABUJA – Nigerian Electricity Regulatory Commission (NERC), on Friday made clarifications on the trending reports that it approved tariff increase for Distribution Companies otherwise known as DisCos. The media was on Thursday awash with the news of approval to DisCos for an increase in tariff by NERC. But Mr Garba Sanusi, the chairman of NERC, at a press briefing, gave clarifications on the issue saying the tariff increase was effected since December 2021, saying that it was not a new hike but was just uploaded on the Commission’s website on Thursday. -Advertisement- Sanusi, who spoke to the press in the company of Aisha Mohammed, Commissioner, Consumer Affairs, and Dr Musiliu Olalekan Oseni, Vice Chairman, and Commissioner, Market Competition and Rates among other management staff of NERC, insisted that the Commission has not approved a new tariff increase but the report gave the impression that it was a recent increase. The chairman explained that it is part of the functions of the commission to review tariffs considering the inflationary and exchange rate fluctuations but a new tariff increase has not taken place. Recall that on its website on Thursday, the Commission published a review of a tariff increase for six Distribution Companies (DisCos) with effect from December 2021. The DisCos include Port Harcourt Electricity Distribution Company (PHEDC); Jos Electricity Distribution Company (JEDC); Kano Electricity Distribution Company (KEDC); Kaduna Electricity Distribution Company (KEDC); Ikeja Electricity Distribution Company (IKEDC) and Ibadan Electricity Distribution Company (IBEDC). The document was issued on December 29, 2021, and signed by NERC chairman, Sanusi Garba and, vice chairman, Musiliu Oseni said that the new tariff took effect from February 2022. POLL The commission said that some of the indices considered for the tariff increase include gas price, inflation, exchange rate, US inflation rate and available generation capacity adding that these indices shall be reviewed every six months to update the tariffs with changes in the indices as applicable in line with the multi-year tariff order (MYTO).